
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `listres` baraye didane resource-haye X server (mesle font-ha va rang-ha) estefade mishavad. In dastoor etela'at ra az X server migirad va aan ra namayesh midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-all`  --> 👀 Namayesh hameye resource-ha, hata anha ke default hastand.
    🔹 `-fonts`  --> 🖋️ Fagat list font-ha ra namayesh bede.
    🔹 `-colors` --> 🎨 Fagat list rang-ha ra namayesh bede.
    🔹 `-display <hostname>:<displaynumber>` --> 🖥️ Be yek X display khass vasl sho. Agar display ghabel dastras nabashad, az in estefade konid.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ listres

    🔹 Namayesh resource-haye X server default.

    $ listres -all -fonts

    🔹 Namayesh hameye font-ha, hata font-haye default.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ listres -fonts | grep "Times"

    🔹 List hameye font-haye X server ra namayesh mide ke dar nameshoon "Times" darand.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `listres` command is used to list X server resources, such as fonts and colors. It retrieves information from the X server and displays it.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-all`  --> 👀 Display all resources, including defaults.
    🔹 `-fonts`  --> 🖋️ Only list fonts.
    🔹 `-colors` --> 🎨 Only list colors.
    🔹 `-display <hostname>:<displaynumber>` --> 🖥️ Connect to a specific X display. Use this if the default display is not accessible.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ listres

    🔹 Display the default X server resources.

    $ listres -all -fonts

    🔹 Display all fonts, including default fonts.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ listres -fonts | grep "Times"

    🔹 Lists all X server fonts that contain "Times" in their name.

